## # A tibble: 1 × 3

#compute 99% prediction level after conversion to noraml distribution by transformTukey
colgpa.t = transformTukey(data$colgpa, plotit=TRUE)

## 
##     lambda      W Shapiro.p.value
## 450  1.225 0.9934       6.344e-13
## 
## if (lambda >  0){TRANS = x ^ lambda} 
## if (lambda == 0){TRANS = log(x)} 
## if (lambda <  0){TRANS = -1 * x ^ lambda}

#since lambda >0 ,we use TRANS = x ^ lambda

mncolgpa.t <- mean(colgpa.t)
sdcolgpa.t <- sd(colgpa.t)
n.gpa <- nrow(data)
uPI.colgpa.t <- mncolgpa.t + (qt(0.995, df = (n.gpa-1))*sdcolgpa.t *sqrt(1+1/n.gpa))
lPI.colgpa.t <- mncolgpa.t - (qt(0.995, df = (n.gpa-1))*sdcolgpa.t *sqrt(1+1/n.gpa))
cbind(uPI.colgpa.t, lPI.colgpa.t)
##      uPI.colgpa.t lPI.colgpa.t
## [1,]     5.891648     0.774644
lPI.colgpa.t2 <- (lPI.colgpa.t)^(1/1.225)
uPI.colgpa.t2<- (uPI.colgpa.t)^(1/1.225)  

print(cbind(lPI.colgpa.t2,uPI.colgpa.t2),digits=4)
##      lPI.colgpa.t2 uPI.colgpa.t2
## [1,]        0.8118         4.254

  1. Set up and test the following hypotheses:
  1. Is the mean colgpa for male athlete students different from male non-athlete students? (1.5 marks)
  2. Is the proportion of students with a colgpa of more than 3.5, less than 12%? Use alpha=0.01 (2.5 marks)
male_athlete <- data %>% filter(female == 0 & athlete == 1)
non_male_athlete <- data %>% filter(female == 0 & athlete == 0)

t.test(male_athlete$colgpa, non_male_athlete$colgpa)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  male_athlete$colgpa and non_male_athlete$colgpa
## t = -6.1728, df = 179.5, p-value = 4.353e-09
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3979833 -0.2051716
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2.306980  2.608557
#H0:  mean `colgpa` for male athlete students = mean `colgpa` for male non-athlete students; 
#H1:  mean `colgpa` for male athlete students != mean `colgpa` for male non-athlete students
#The Welch t test results show we have sufficient evidence to reject H0 (p = 4.353e-09 <0.05). Hence, we can conclude statistically that there is significant difference between mean `colgpa` for male athlete students and mean `colgpa` for male non-athlete students, at the 5% level of significance.

data_n <- data %>% mutate(more = ifelse(data$colgpa >3.5,1,0))

Portfolio Management (total 15 marks) Consider you are a portfolio manager in charge of a simple portfolio which consists of two public traded stocks in Singapore Exchange (SGX) market, 5Xnergy (SGX: 5X) and EverGreen Tech (SGX: EG). The stocks are traded in minimum unit of one share. Given the current and predicted stock prices, the portfolio manager who starts with zero holding, decides the holding positions of the stocks in portfolio, i.e. the number of shares, at the beginning of a financial year and holds the portfolio for a year. Below is the information about the two stocks: Risk of a stock is the standard deviation of the predicted price in one year. Assume that the total risk of the portfolio is a linear combination of risk of the stocks in the portfolio, weighted by the positions, i.e. total risk of a portfolio consisting of a #shares of 5X and b #shares of EG is 0.37a + 18.21b. The total risk of the portfolio should not exceed 50,000 SGD. The portfolio manager is endowed with an investment budget of one million SGD and tries to maximize the total return of the portfolio.

  1. Write down the decision variables, the objective function, and ALL relevant constraints that apply for this optimization problem in a table formulation. Do NOT solve the problem yet. (5 marks)
  2. Solve your formulated optimization problem in R. What are the optimal holdings of the two stocks in the portfolio? What is the optimal total return of the portfolio? (3 marks)
  3. Predicted price in one year for each stock is naturally random from the current perspective of the portfolio manager. Suppose that predicted price in one year of each stock follows a log-normal distribution with mean mu_i and sigma_i where i = 5X, EG, provided in the table below. Use Monte Carlo method to simulate 100 predicted prices in one year for both stocks and answer the following questions. (2 marks) • What is the simulated standard deviation of predicted price for each stock, i.e. risk of each stock? (1 mark) • What is the average optimal total return of the portfolio? (3 marks) • What is the probability that the optimal total return of the portfolio is less than 250,000 SGD? (1 mark)
  1. Maximize total return using decision variables \(X_1\), \(X_2\) return = 19.2 \(X_1\) + 21.9 \(X_2\)
    Subject to
    cost Constraint 15.6 \(X_1\) + 3.5 \(X_2\) \(\leq\) 1000000
    risk Constraint 0.37 \(X_1\) + 18.21 \(X_2\) \(\leq\) 50000
    Non-Negativity and Integer Constraint \(X_1\) \(X_2\) are both integer and positive 
objective.fn1 <- c(19.2,21.9)

const.mat1 <- matrix(c(15.6, 3.5,
                       0.37, 18.21),
                     ncol = 2,
                     byrow = TRUE)

const.dir1 <- c("<=","<=")
const.rhs1 <- c(1000000,50000)

lp.solution1 <- lp("max",objective.fn1, const.mat1 , const.dir1, const.rhs1, compute.sens = TRUE,all.int = TRUE)

lp.solution1
## Success: the objective function is 1256252
lp.solution1$solution
## [1] 63777  1449

optimal return is $1256252 , this could be achieved by purchasing 63777 shares of 5X and 1449 shares of EG

lm1 <- lm(totacc~t+spdlaw+beltlaw ,tf)

  1. Interpret the coefficient estimators before spdlaw and beltlaw, respectively. (2 marks) Assuming the model is valid, please explain (by proposing possible theory) and make sense of the sign (direction of the effect) of coefficient estimators before spdlaw and betlaw. (2 marks)

spdlaw : -1318.83 :If the speed law is implemented and taken effect, it comes 1, the mean total number of road accidents is expected to decrease by 1318.83 on average than when it is not implemented.This is because limit the speed of the car can decrease the probability of accidents as drivers have more time to react to potential dangers and accidents. beltlaw : 4076.69 :If the belt law is implemented and taken effect, it comes 1, the mean total number of road accidents is expected to increase by 4076.69 on average than when it is not implemented. This is because drives tend to be more arrogant as they believe they are protected well by the belt so they drive more carelessly.

Limitation : The p value for spdlaw is larger than 0.05, means that at 5% level of significance, we do not have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis that the coefficient is zero. Hence, spdlaw coefficient is statistically insignificant.

Yes. Number of vehicles on road increases as time progresses as cars are becoming necessities to people’s daily lives, and they are getting more and more affordable.
